#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:5
msgid ""
"Have you ever had a borrowed `Option<T>` and tried to match on it? You "
"probably wrote this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:9
#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:23
msgid "\"hello\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:12
#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:26
msgid "\"s is: {}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:17
msgid ""
"In Rust 2015, this would fail to compile, and you would have to write the "
"following instead:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:21
msgid "// Rust 2015\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:31
msgid ""
"Rust 2018, by contrast, will infer the `&`s and `ref`s, and your original "
"code will Just Work."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:34
msgid ""
"This affects not just `match`, but patterns everywhere, such as in `let` "
"statements, closure arguments, and `for` loops."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:37
msgid "More details"
msgstr "更多詳情"

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:39
msgid ""
"The mental model of patterns has shifted a bit with this change, to bring it "
"into line with other aspects of the language. For example, when writing a "
"`for` loop, you can iterate over borrowed contents of a collection by "
"borrowing the collection itself:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:50
msgid ""
"The idea is that an `&T` can be understood as a _borrowed view of `T`_, and "
"so when you iterate, match, or otherwise destructure a `&T` you get a "
"borrowed view of its internals as well."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/ownership-and-lifetimes/default-match-bindings.md:54
msgid ""
"More formally, patterns have a \"binding mode,\" which is either by value "
"(`x`), by reference (`ref x`), or by mutable reference (`ref mut x`). In "
"Rust 2015, `match` always started in by-value mode, and required you to "
"explicitly write `ref` or `ref mut` in patterns to switch to a borrowing "
"mode. In Rust 2018, the type of the value being matched informs the binding "
"mode, so that if you match against an `&Option<String>` with a `Some` "
"variant, you are put into `ref` mode automatically, giving you a borrowed "
"view of the internal data. Similarly, `&mut Option<String>` would give you a "
"`ref mut` view."
msgstr ""
